In Italian, feminine words ending in -a form their plural by changing the -a to -e.  LIRE is no exception.  

Since "currency" can either signify singular or plural, there's nothing wrong with the clue or answer.

@Pao Ton
In Italy we ALWAYS pluralized "lira" to "lire", back when we had our own monetary system. We said "una lira", but "cento (100) lire". In fact, when the euro came in, it was a struggle for many Italians to stop pluralizing it to "euri" and follow government recommendations to leave the word invariable.

With regard to the Mini crossword, the clue said "currency replaced by the euro in Italy". The currency that was replaced by "the euro" was "the lira", and so "lire" doesn't fit. But it's absolutely not true that Italians treated "lira" as invariable. I suppose Americans, back in the day, said "liras".

@Sharon 

It is true that Americans (and other anglophones) pluralize foreign words with the English -s unless the plural is extremely well-known, but that's irrelevant here.

What you and others are missing is that "currency" can mean "cash"; if there's a wad of LIRE on the table, you can call it a pile of "currency".  The entry LIRE has been clued as currency many times in the past, and it is not considered an error, or else it would have changed by now.

