SORTA related to this discussion, estates lawyers have traditionally distinguished males from females, whether orally or in writing, in referring to the will-maker as “testator” or  “testatrix” and to the personal representative as “executor” or “executrix”.  However, as  the meaning of neither “testator” nor “executor” was ever restricted so as to mean only a male, I have always nixed the -ix.  

(Only in recent years has the issue of gender arisen for will-drafters.  Apart from the ubiquitous appearance of “his or her”, “he or she”, etc.  in the standard will clauses — now being a few centuries old — it can be a particularly sensitive one where a beneficiary has openly declared to be non-binary and the will-maker wants to acknowledge this.  I’m too old-fashioned to be prepared to use the pronoun “they” in such cases, but creative use of syntax has, so far, enabled me to avoid it when I am prepared to abandon binary terminology.)

